{
  "text": "Let f : C \u2282 Y \u2212\u2192 X \u2283 P be a divisorial extremal neighborhood. Let E be the f -exceptional divisor and \u0393 its center in X. Assume that the general hyperplane section S of X containing \u0393 is DuVal of type E 7 . Then Theorem 4.1 and Proposition 4.7 show that the general member of |O Y | is completely determined by the general member of |O X |. It would be of interest to know if this holds in general. If it does then one would be able to find the general member of any |O Y | by working out just a special example. Remark 4.9. Surface germs C \u2282 Z as in the previous proposition have terminal QGorenstein smoothings Y that produce divisorial extremal neighborhoods f : C \u2282 Y \u2212\u2192 X \u220b P of type other that E 7,k , i.e., Z is the general member of |O Y | but the general hyperplane section S of X containg \u0393 is not E 7 . The type of the extremal neighborhoods associated to Q-Gorenstein smoothings Y of Z is determined by the general member of | \u2212 K Y |. The way to get smoothings Y with prescribed general anticanonical members is the following. Let Q be the singular point of Z. Let \u03c0 : Z \u2032 \u2212\u2192 Z be the index 1 cover of Q \u2208 Z. This is given by an equation of the form g(x, y, z) = 0 and it has a Z 2 -action. Let Y \u2032 be a smoothing given by g(x, y, z) + tf (x, y, z, t) = 0 such that the Z 2 -action extends. In addition choose it in such a way such that the general hyperplane section S \u2032 in the eigenspace of \u2212K Y \u2032 is DuVal. Then S = S \u2032 /Z 2 is the general member of | \u2212 K Y | and it is also DuVal. All finite covers of DuVal singularities have been classified by M. Reid [CITATION_1] and looking at the list one knows what the S \u2032 must be in order to get the desired S. Next the deformation Q \u2208 Y lifts to a deformation Y of Z and extending the contraction f : Z \u2212\u2192 H to Y we get an extremal neighborhood f : Y \u2212\u2192 X with the desired invariants.",
